---
Ashborn orientation toward forge and fire translates into a specific relationship with healing: Ashborn practitioners tend to understand restoration as reforging — returning a damaged system to operational integrity through concentrated application of force.
The Priest tradition's compound-condition methodology aligns with Ashborn attention to integrated system function; Ashborn Priests have developed reputations for effectiveness in high-intensity simultaneous-casualty situations where the standard triage model fails.
Their willingness to engage compound conditions without sequential separation produces faster outcomes in situations where sequential treatment would be too slow; the Ember Wardens' integration of Ashborn Priests into rapid-response teams reflects this capability.
The tension is that Ashborn direct-action orientation conflicts with the sustained miracle-channel methodology's requirement for extended focused stillness — Ashborn Priests tend to be better at acute intervention than at the hours-long sustained channel work that represents the tradition's most technically demanding specialty.
